label chapter13:

    # [Scene: Glass Pier | Dusk — Press Night]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A swelling, urgent synth; a high metronomic beat like a heartbeat under it]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Camera shutters, murmured gasps, the metallic rasp of a megawatt crane in the distance; a child's recorded voice threading through the speakers]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_2 at full_bg
    "You remember the exact instant you said yes—the little nod you gave Ori beneath the sailcloth, the way your fingers tightened on the notebook—and now the city is watching what you let loose."

    "The mural breathes. Tiny recorded mouths—neighbors, children, Old Mara telling a reef story—rise and fall on the speakers in a cadence that feels like a pulse" "My pa taught me to mend nets…', 'When the water came, we moved the stove…', 'We don't want a fence. We want a home."
    "You can smell salt and solder, coffee and the acrid tang of stage smoke. Up close, the metal feels warm from the work-lights; the seaglass trembles in your palm like something alive. Cameras pivot; a drone"
    "hovers at your shoulder like a second gull. You are adrenaline and lullaby at once—hands raw from wiring, throat tight with the speech you almost gave."
    show ori_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ori_navarro "You ready for them to see us? For them to hear them?"
    show ava_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ava_maren "They'll listen. For a moment. But listening isn't the same as listening to keep us."

    ori_navarro "Then we'll make them want to keep us. Make it impossible to look away."
    "You laugh because you have to, a sound that cracks. The laugh is a small release; it sparks a round of applause from one side of the pier and a click of skepticism from the other—the investors’ tent—where LED logos flicker like distant stars."
    hide ori_navarro
    hide ava_maren

    scene bg ch13_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A corporate PA, then Calder's voice—smooth, measured—over the public feed.]
    show calder_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    calder_voss "Beautiful. Heartfelt. Harborlight has always been a place of stories. But stories do not stop storms. We are proposing safeguards that will ensure lives are secured, not sentimentalized."
    "The crowd exhales, some in indignation, some in agreement—emotion rearranged into policy language. You feel the air tilt, the tide of opinion changing with the ease of a practiced hand."
    "A reporter shouts a question you cannot hear. Calder smiles with a measured kindness and lets the implication slide into the broadcast: sentimental communities make humane headlines; humane headlines make efficient solutions seem necessary."
    "From somewhere behind the cranes, a muted phone buzzes with investor messaging—'cute,' 'socially resonant,' 'leverage for relocation.' The word lands like a stone in a quiet pond and ripples outward."

    menu:
        "Step forward to respond on the mic":
            "You move to the microphone, the metal cold and certain beneath your palm. Your throat fills with every tenure clause and every face you've promised to keep. You open your mouth—an answering tide—but the comms tech hisses that the feed is controlled and your channel is delayed. The moment fractures into applause and a legal statement."
        "Stand back and let Ori's work speak":
            "You step away from the mic and watch Ori press his palms to the mural, guiding a ribbon of light. The crowd leans in. Cameras catch his hands; your absence makes the image of the community more complete—but your silence tastes like a concession you did not consent to."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues below."
    "It starts as theater—then it becomes leverage. The mural is republished across feeds: snippets of children, the slow hands of Old Mara, a shot of your notebook clutched to your hip. The city pauses; for several minutes the press cadence stutters and a different kind of attention blooms."
    "A man in a suit claps politely near the investor tent. Across from him, a younger executive scrolls through responses, lips pursed, and taps a short memo with a thumb. That memo moves faster than the tide."
    "You feel it—the change in wind—before you read the words. Security teams begin to fan out. Not the polite municipal stewards you’re used to, but firm, efficient people in neutral jackets, radios warm against their shoulders."
    "They tape off a perimeter with yellow, their movements precise; they do not speak loudly. The sound is the sound of containment."
    "Ori sees it too. He tugs a strand of hair from his forehead and his fingers are suddenly small. He crosses the slats of the pier to you, voice low and taut."
    show ori_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ori_navarro "They like the art. They love the image. They'll say it's why we need the model."
    show ava_maren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    ava_maren "They're framing us as an object, Ori. A reason, not an owner. We needed tenure, not an exhibit."

    ori_navarro "We made it feel like home. That's not nothing."
    "You open your mouth and close it. The speakers play a child's laugh; someone in the crowd sobs quietly. Everything is amplified into a thousand rooms where it will become something else."

    menu:
        "Step in front of a security line, refuse to let them tape off a planter":
            "You place your boots on the wet plank and plant yourself in front of the planter as a slow-moving officer approaches. People shout—some your name, some orders. A clipboard is held toward you; a badge is shown; the officer's voice is a sanded kind. You feel the weight of every family who might be forced later to lift their plants and leave. For a heartbeat it seems you could stop the rope. Then two others move in; the tape snakes around you anyway."
        "Help neighbors fold up planters quietly":
            "You grab a crate and lift, shoulders burning. You help an older woman fold a planter into a tarpaulin. Her hands shake as she tucks basil into plastic. The work is small and human and meaningfully practical; it does not stop the memo, but it keeps someone from being alone while the world recalibrates their life."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues below."
    "The memo reaches the hands that matter. It is not a broadcast piece; it is a quiet authorization—'increase relocation efforts'—the kind of document that never screams but executes. You don't see the signature on the tablet; you feel the consequence of the sentence threading through the pier like a current."
    "Calder's PR pivots immediately, economically: aesthetic admiration reframed as rationale. He speaks of 'efficiency,' of 'protective corridors,' of 'the responsibility to save lives.' On-screen, his jaw tightens for a fraction of a second—just enough to tell you that his kindness is an instrument."

    calder_voss "We must do more than honor memory. We must guarantee survival. That will require bold choices."
    "The word 'bold' is a blade. Cameras cut to your mural; then they cut to a corporate blueprint overlay, a proposed levee line annotated with rectangles labeled 'Relocation Zones'. The juxtaposition is clean. The narrative edits itself: from 'look at these people' to 'these people need protecting from themselves.'"
    "You move through the pier as if underwater: light refracted, voices muffled. Neighbors fold up their planters, kiss their hands to fragile leaves, tuck seeds into pockets. The communal life you built in shared work tangles"
    "into shopping lists and legal forms in the hands of clerks you will never meet."
    "Ori catches your sleeve and — for the first time tonight — he cannot find a joke that fits. He presses something into your palm: a small seaglass charm threaded with a salvaged circuit fragment, the two elements soldered together with an impatient tenderness."
    hide calder_voss
    hide ori_navarro
    hide ava_maren

    scene bg ch13_3be532_4 at full_bg
    "You close your fingers over it. The charm is heavier than it looks. You feel the texture of the wire, a faint heat from where they soldered it minutes ago. It is both a thing of"
    "beauty and a talisman against forgetting. You do not know whether it's for luck, guilt, or promise; it does not matter which."
    show ava_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ava_maren "We made something real."
    show ori_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ori_navarro "We did. They just... turned it into a reason."
    "You try to put the grievance elsewhere—into Calder's smile, into the investors' memos—but it lands in your chest like a stone. The murmur of the crowd swells and, for a terrifying second, you imagine all the mural's small recordings as driftwood: pretty to see, useless to stop a tide."
    "Calder's feed cuts to a live interview. He speaks the language of safety and inevitability, his sentences clean and unassailable. You feel the reporters' questions sharpen toward policy; the mural becomes a symbol in a headline that will justify moving people for 'their own good.'"

    "A young security supervisor steps toward the crowd and reads an official-sounding line into a portable mic" "For public safety, this area will be regulated per municipal directive."
    "Someone cries—soft, broken—behind you. Old Mara's shawl is a small sea on her lap as she tucks a string of beads into a pouch. Jun is there somewhere in the press crush, camera steady, mouth a"
    "thin line. There is an ache in your throat that tastes like both salt and old blood."
    "You move along the mural's edge. The lights are still bright, the speakers still playing neighbors' voices, but the rhythm is fractured now—burst into segments by legalese and news bites. The visual that was meant to"
    "humanize has been folded into a case study for why the very people it portrays should be managed."
    "You think, with a cold clarity, of tenure forms, of councilrooms, of lawyers with polite faces. You think of the years of careful work, the meetings with boards, the promises you coaxed from weary officials—how fragile"
    "those agreements feel under the weight of an economy that prefers a single engineered solution to the messy, costly justice of community rights."
    "Ori watches you watch the pier being sectioned off. He reaches to take your hand and for once does not pat the small of your back with a joke. Instead, he speaks softly, the way one might speak to a child stepping into a puddle too deep."

    ori_navarro "Whatever happens—this mattered. To them. To us."
    "You look at him, and something in you unravels and resettles. You want to argue—about strategy, about the next move, about whether to fight in a courtroom or in the streets—but your voice is a thread pulled taut."

    ava_maren "It matters and they'll still use it to move us."

    ori_navarro "Then we keep making things that matter. We keep putting our work where it can be seen. We don't give them the language to erase us."
    "You feel the truth of both words like two sides of a horizon. Neither will stop the memo already signed. Neither will undo the yellow tape being clipped into place."
    hide ava_maren
    hide ori_navarro

    scene bg ch13_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The speakers play Old Mara's voice—"We are water people."—and someone in the crowd begins to hum.]
    "You step away from the tape. Your boots make a soft slap on the wet boards. The charm heavy in your palm is a small, private proof that something true was made tonight. The lights glitter"
    "on the glass like a field of caught stars, and for a second the beauty burns with a clean pain."
    "You want to carry every person on your back. You want to haul the memo into the light and show its seams. You want to fold the cranes into paper boats and set them adrift. Instead you walk."
    "The pier narrows, and beyond it the glass of the corporate tents reflects a sky thick with the promise of another storm. The mural plays on behind you, voices spilling into a world that will choose what to keep and what to catalog."
    "Ori falls into step beside you without asking. He does not speak for a long time. When he finally says something, his voice is small and steady, as if testing an old shore."
    show ori_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ori_navarro "Come with me tomorrow. We'll salvage what we can, catalog the stories, put them where they can't be turned into props."
    show ava_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ava_maren "Yes.' (The word is both a promise and a surrender.) 'We'll make records. We'll keep the names."
    "He squeezes your hand—the pressure neither here nor there. For a moment you allow yourself to imagine a different ending: tide turned by community law, Calder stepping back, tenure security assured. The image is bright, impossible, like a lighthouse in fog."
    "Then the memo presses its shadow across your memory. Tonight's applause becomes tomorrow's justification. The city's appetite is not for restitution; it is for an image that can be managed."
    "You stop near the end of the pier and turn to look back. The mural gleams; someone has draped a length of plain white cloth across one corner—an attempt, perhaps, at reclaiming the image. The lights"
    "catch on the cloth and for an unbearable second it looks as if the community has hung a flag."
    "Ori presses the seaglass charm into your palm once more. His face is close; you see the outline of his mouth setup for a joke that does not come."
    "He murmurs, almost to himself, almost to you:"

    ori_navarro "I wish... I wish it had been enough."
    "You swallow. The word 'enough' lands like a verdict."
    "You fold the charm into your pocket and feel its shape—proof, memory, weight. You let your fingers close around it until the metal cools."
    "You walk away from the mural. Behind you the speakers keep speaking, and Calder's face fades back to the screens where it will be edited, quoted, and republished. The security tape flutters faintly; the cranes keep casting long patient shadows."
    "You walk into the rain that comes without drama—just a steady, thin curtain that makes everything look like water-color blurring at the edges. Your jacket soaks and the salt prickles on your skin. You think of"
    "all the small lives folded up tonight, the plants bagged like apologies, the plans that will need rewrites."
    "You will not say the word 'defeat' aloud. It will not help. But you will hold the memory of the mural like a ledger—evidence of what people can make when they are seen. You will keep"
    "it in the pocket of your jacket, pressed against the charm and the notebook and the notes that smell like tide."
    hide ori_navarro
    hide ava_maren

    scene bg ch13_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, low chord that does not resolve—sustain and fade into the sound of rain and distant thunder.]
    "You step off the pier and onto the boardwalk. Behind you, under the glow that still holds for others, the mural plays on—beautiful, persuasive, and ultimately reshaped into a reason to move the things it had tried to protect."

